lasses in HS, but around the world English is treated as an additional core class. %0a%0aI guess the main thing that is lost in languages going extinct is culture as you have explained. I guess a similar issue is that written language is becoming more extinct. I watch more Youtube and TikTok than ever and none of my classes use textbooks.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210203-073420-387480#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210211-134025-768050#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-11.02.2021 - 05:40-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210211-134025-768050 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!NathanW%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Why we learn dying languages'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aI think it could also be interesting to consider why people sometimes learn dead languages. For example, I think it's not uncommon for some people to take Latin in high school even though it is a dead language. So it seems like people may still get some useful things out of dead languages beyond obvious communication aspects of the language. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210211-134025-768050#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:Section: :)%0a(:Category: PracticeCategory:)
